---
// Security & Data Residency page (scope: on-prem). Highest claim-risk page.
//
// Art direction: the confidential institutional dossier established by the Home
// page. A single .hero (one h1, single editorial column), then numbered
// SectionShell sections separated only by full-width hairline rules and spacing,
// content at a comfortable reading measure, full-width children opting out via
// .ds__bleed. One deliberate dark surface, the closing CTA band. Warm off-white
// base, single deep forest accent, near-black ink. Red appears only inside the
// data-boundary diagram's own markup (residency risk), never on page chrome.
//
// Claim guardrail: never assert a framework is satisfied, certified, or ready;
// sovereignty stays on-prem scoped and qualified in the same sentence; no cost
// proof and no named-vendor cost story belong on this page; the court sentence
// appears only in its permitted verbatim form, no date, no case, no provider.
// LEGAL-REVIEW markers are invisible Astro comments only.
//
// Zero client JS, no script tags. The data-boundary SVG is inlined at build
// time via ?raw inside Figure, which ships no runtime and re-tints via the .d-*
// class hooks. This .astro page is not content-lint scanned (lint scans only
// MDX under src/content/pages), so no lint claim wrappers belong here.
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionShell from '../components/SectionShell.astro';
import Figure from '../components/Figure.astro';

// Build-time inlined diagram. data-boundary.svg uses the red d-risk hooks for
// the residency-risk egress path; everything else rides the forest accent.
import dataBoundary from '../assets/diagrams/data-boundary.svg?raw';
---

<Base
  title="Data Sovereignty and Residency for Regulated AI"
  description="Residency is where your data sits. Sovereignty is who can be ordered to hand it over. On-prem Hive keeps every inference inside your own infrastructure, so there is no third party left to compel."
  structuredData={{
    breadcrumbs: [
      { name: 'Home', url: 'https://hive.scubed.co/' },
      { name: 'Security and Data Residency', url: 'https://hive.scubed.co/security' },
    ],
    securityFaq: true,
  }}
>
  {/* ============ HERO (single editorial column, the only h1) ============ */}
  <section class="hero" aria-labelledby="hero-h1">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="hero__col load-rise">
        <p class="hero__meta">
          <span class="hero__tag">Security</span>
          <span class="hero__metasep" aria-hidden="true">&#183;</span>
          <span class="hero__tag">Data residency</span>
          <span class="hero__metasep" aria-hidden="true">&#183;</span>
          <span class="hero__tag">On-prem</span>
        </p>
        <h1 id="hero-h1" class="hero__h1">
          Residency is where your data sits. Sovereignty is who can be ordered
          to hand it over.
        </h1>
        {/* LEGAL-REVIEW */}
        <p class="lede">
          Most "data stays in your region" promises solve the first and leave
          the second untouched. On the on-prem Hive deployment, your data stays
          inside your own infrastructure, so there is no third party left to
          compel.
        </p>
        <div class="cta-row">
          <a class="cta cta--primary tap-target" href="/book-a-demo">Book a Demo</a>
          <a class="cta cta--ghost tap-target" href="#architecture">See how it works</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ============ 01 THE DISTINCTION THAT MATTERS ============ */}
  <SectionShell numeral="01" label="The distinction that matters" id="distinction-h2">
    <h2 class="section-h2 section-h2--lead">
      A local datacentre run by an out-of-jurisdiction company is still
      reachable under that company's law.
    </h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Data residency means the bytes are physically located in a chosen
        country. It is a real property and it matters. It is not the same as
        data sovereignty, which is about which jurisdiction governs the company
        that operates the infrastructure.
      </p>
      <p>
        A cloud provider answers to the law of the jurisdiction it is controlled
        from, wherever its datacentres are. Placing your data in that provider's
        local region changes where the bytes sit. It does not change who can be
        ordered to produce them. Sovereignty is reached only when there is no
        out-of-jurisdiction third party in the path at all, and the strongest
        version of that is hardware you own and operate yourself.
        {/* LEGAL-REVIEW */}
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="ds__bleed">
      <Figure
        fig="Fig. 1"
        svg={dataBoundary}
        caption="With Hive on-prem, the boundary has no outbound path. Without it, your data follows a path out to an external cloud, into a jurisdiction that may not be only yours."
        ariaLabel="On the left, a boundary contains your data and the model with no outbound path. On the right, a path shows your data leaving your network to an external cloud under another jurisdiction."
      />
    </div>
  </SectionShell>

  {/* ============ 02 WHAT ON-PREM REMOVES ============ */}
  <SectionShell numeral="02" label="What on-prem removes" id="removes-h2">
    <h2 class="section-h2 section-h2--lead">
      Two ways your data leaves your control, and how on-prem closes both.
    </h2>

    <ul class="ds__bleed cards cards--2" role="list">
      <li class="card card--static">
        <h3 class="card__h3">Cross-jurisdiction reach</h3>
        <p class="card__body">
          A cloud provider can be compelled, under the law it answers to, to
          disclose customer data regardless of where that data is physically
          stored. The US CLOUD Act is one well-known instance of this general
          rule. Residency does not defeat it, because the obligation attaches to
          the provider, not to the datacentre. On-prem Hive removes the provider
          from the equation, so there is nothing for such an order to reach.
          {/* LEGAL-REVIEW */}
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="card card--static">
        <h3 class="card__h3">Litigation discovery</h3>
        <p class="card__body">
          Prompts and responses sent to a third-party AI service are records
          held by another party. They are discoverable, subject to subpoena and
          preservation, and outside your control once they have left. On-prem
          inference keeps those records inside your own systems, where your
          existing legal holds and retention policies already govern them.
          {/* LEGAL-REVIEW */}
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>

    {/* Court sentence: verbatim, do not edit */}
    <p class="prose__after court-line">
      A US court has already ordered a major AI provider to preserve chat logs.
    </p>
  </SectionShell>

  {/* ============ 03 THE ARCHITECTURE ============ */}
  <SectionShell numeral="03" label="The architecture" id="architecture">
    <h2 class="section-h2 section-h2--lead">
      When the data never leaves, there is nothing to compel.
    </h2>
    <p class="prose prose--single">
      The exposure exists because a third party holds your data. Hive's on-prem
      deployment is built so that no third party ever does.
    </p>

    <ul class="ticklist" role="list">
      <li class="ticklist__item">
        Open-weight model weights run entirely on your hardware.
      </li>
      <li class="ticklist__item">
        Every inference executes locally.
      </li>
      <li class="ticklist__item">
        No prompt, no response, and no document calls an external API or leaves
        your network boundary.
        {/* LEGAL-REVIEW */}
      </li>
    </ul>
  </SectionShell>

  {/* ============ 04 DESIGNED-FOR CONTROLS, NOT CERTIFICATIONS ============ */}
  <SectionShell numeral="04" label="Designed-for controls, not certifications" id="controls-h2">
    <h2 class="section-h2 section-h2--lead">
      Not a compliance certification. A control architecture you can audit.
    </h2>
    <p class="prose prose--single">
      Hive is designed for on-prem data residency, and customers validate
      regulatory fit with their own counsel. The controls below are
      architectural facts you can inspect, not badges we claim.
    </p>

    <ul class="ticklist" role="list">
      <li class="ticklist__item">The model runs inside your network.</li>
      <li class="ticklist__item">The inference path has no outbound call.</li>
      <li class="ticklist__item">You hold the hardware, the keys, and the logs.</li>
    </ul>
  </SectionShell>

  {/* ============ 05 HOW ON-PREM CONTROL MAPS TO YOUR OBLIGATIONS ============ */}
  <SectionShell numeral="05" label="Designed to support, verify with counsel" id="mapping-h2">
    <h2 class="section-h2 section-h2--lead">
      Hive provides the control architecture. Your auditor confirms the fit.
    </h2>
    <p class="prose prose--single">
      The following is general information, not legal advice. Hive is not
      compliant with, certified for, or ready for any of these frameworks, and
      we are not pursuing such a certification. What we describe is the on-prem
      control architecture Hive provides to help you meet obligations you
      already carry, mapped to the relevant area. Confirm scope and current text
      against your own auditor or counsel.
      {/* LEGAL-REVIEW */}
    </p>

    <ul class="ds__bleed proofs proofs--two" role="list">
      <li class="proof__item">
        <span class="proof__label">Finance</span>
        <p class="proof__text">
          Hive provides the on-prem control architecture to help financial
          institutions meet OSFI Guideline B-10 (third-party and outsourcing
          risk), OSFI Guideline B-13 (technology and cyber risk), SOC 2, and PCI
          DSS obligations, among others. Keeping data on hardware you control
          simplifies third-party isolation and audit, and removes the
          cross-border transfer step from the picture. Validate with your own
          auditor.
          {/* LEGAL-REVIEW */}
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="proof__item">
        <span class="proof__label">Healthcare and privacy</span>
        <p class="proof__text">
          Hive provides the on-prem control architecture to help health and
          privacy obligations under HIPAA (US healthcare), PHIPA (Ontario), and
          PIPEDA (Canada), among others. Keeping personal health information on
          hardware the custodian controls keeps it under the custodian's direct
          accountability, with no external service provider in the data path.
          HIPAA applies to US healthcare only and does not cover banking.
          Validate with your own counsel.
          {/* LEGAL-REVIEW */}
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="proof__item">
        <span class="proof__label">Legal</span>
        <p class="proof__text">
          Professional duties of confidentiality, such as those under the Law
          Society of Ontario rules in Ontario and SRA rules in the UK, expect
          client confidences to stay protected. On-prem keeps client matter data
          inside the firm, with no third-party processor in the chain. Validate
          with your own counsel.
          {/* LEGAL-REVIEW */}
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="proof__item">
        <span class="proof__label">Government and defence</span>
        <p class="proof__text">
          For environments that permit no outbound network path, Hive supports
          air-gapped and offline deployment, so inference runs with no external
          connectivity at all. Validate suitability for your accreditation
          requirements with your own authority.
          {/* LEGAL-REVIEW */}
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="proof__item">
        <span class="proof__label">Region notes</span>
        <p class="proof__text">
          In the UK, FCA and PRA SS2/21 cover material-outsourcing audit rights,
          documented exit plans, and concentration risk, and UK GDPR covers
          international-transfer controls. On-prem removes the material-outsourcing
          relationship and the international-transfer step. In Canada, Quebec Law
          25 requires a privacy impact assessment before transferring personal
          information outside Quebec, and on-prem removes that transfer trigger.
          Validate current text and scope with your own counsel.
          {/* LEGAL-REVIEW */}
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </SectionShell>

  {/* ============ 06 HIVE CLOUD IS DIFFERENT ============ */}
  <SectionShell numeral="06" label="Hive Cloud is different" id="cloud-h2">
    <h2 class="section-h2 section-h2--lead">
      We state the boundary plainly.
    </h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        The hosted Hive tiers run on third-party infrastructure. They run only
        on in-region infrastructure under your own jurisdiction, which removes
        the cross-jurisdiction reach an out-of-region host would carry, but they
        still do not carry the same data-residency properties as the on-prem
        edition. If your requirement is that data stays on hardware you control,
        the on-prem edition is the one that meets it.
        {/* LEGAL-REVIEW */}
      </p>
    </div>
  </SectionShell>

  {/* ============ 07 DISCLAIMER (verbatim, names S Cubed) ============ */}
  <SectionShell numeral="07" label="Disclaimer" id="disclaimer-h2">
    <p class="disclaimer" role="note">
      Hive's on-prem deployment is designed so that your data does not leave
      your infrastructure. This is an architectural property, not a compliance
      certification. Whether this architecture satisfies your organisation's
      obligations under PIPEDA, HIPAA, or other frameworks is a determination
      your team must make with qualified legal counsel. S Cubed does not provide
      legal or compliance advice.
    </p>
  </SectionShell>

  {/* ============ 08 FAQ ============ */}
  <SectionShell numeral="08" label="Common questions" id="faq-h2">
    <h2 class="section-h2 section-h2--lead">
      Frequently asked questions
    </h2>
    <div class="faq">
      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary class="faq__q">What is the difference between data residency and data sovereignty?</summary>
        <p class="faq__a">
          Residency is where your data physically sits. Sovereignty is which
          jurisdiction governs the company that holds it. A provider's Canadian
          data centre keeps the bytes in Canada, but if that provider is
          foreign-controlled a foreign court order can still reach them.
          On-prem Hive removes the third party from the data path.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary class="faq__q">Can Hive run in an air-gapped environment?</summary>
        <p class="faq__a">
          Yes. Hive runs inference entirely on hardware you own, with no
          outbound network path required, which supports fully air-gapped and
          offline deployments.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </SectionShell>

  {/* ============ CLOSING CTA (ink, the one deliberate dark surface) ============ */}
  <section class="closing" aria-labelledby="closing-h2">
    <div class="shell narrow closing__inner">
      <h2 id="closing-h2" class="section-h2 section-h2--lead closing__h2">
        See it run inside your own network.
      </h2>
      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="cta cta--on-ink tap-target" href="/book-a-demo">Book a Demo</a>
        <a class="cta cta--ghost-ink tap-target" href="/pricing">See Pricing</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  /* =========================================================================
     SHARED TYPE ROLES (dossier kit, copied verbatim from the Home page).
     global.css forces h2..h6 to Inter; .section-h2 re-declares the display
     family so the dossier H2 titles stay Fraunces.
     ========================================================================= */
  .section-h2 {
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: var(--text-h2-dossier);
    line-height: var(--lh-heading);
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    color: var(--text);
    max-width: 22ch;
  }

  .section-h2--lead {
    max-width: 24ch;
  }

  .prose {
    color: var(--text);
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    line-height: var(--lh-body);
  }

  .prose p {
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-5);
    max-width: 68ch;
  }

  .prose p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .prose--single {
    margin: var(--space-5) 0 0;
    max-width: 66ch;
  }

  .prose__after {
    margin: var(--space-7) 0 0;
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--text-muted);
    line-height: var(--lh-body);
    max-width: 68ch;
  }

  .textlink {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-weight: 600;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--accent-line);
    padding-bottom: 1px;
    transition: border-color var(--dur-fast) var(--ease-out);
  }

  .textlink:hover {
    border-bottom-color: var(--accent);
  }

  .narrow {
    max-width: 800px;
  }

  /* The court line reads as page text, not muted, so the fact lands. */
  .court-line {
    color: var(--text);
    font-weight: 600;
    max-width: 60ch;
  }

  /* =========================================================================
     CTA BUTTONS (dossier kit, verbatim). The contrast-safe primary is forest
     fill with an off-white label; the closing band carries the ink variants.
     ========================================================================= */
  .cta-row {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    margin-top: var(--space-7);
  }

  .cta {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    cursor: pointer;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.01em;
    padding: 14px 26px;
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    transition: background-color var(--dur-base) var(--ease-out),
                border-color var(--dur-base) var(--ease-out),
                transform var(--dur-base) var(--ease-out);
  }

  .cta--primary {
    background-color: var(--accent);
    color: var(--bg);
    border: 1px solid var(--accent);
  }

  .cta--primary:hover {
    background-color: var(--accent-hover);
    border-color: var(--accent-hover);
    transform: translateY(-1px);
  }

  .cta--ghost {
    background-color: transparent;
    color: var(--text);
    border: 1px solid var(--border-strong);
  }

  .cta--ghost:hover {
    border-color: var(--text-faint);
    transform: translateY(-1px);
  }

  .cta--on-ink {
    background-color: var(--on-ink);
    color: var(--ink);
    border: 1px solid var(--on-ink);
  }

  .cta--on-ink:hover {
    background-color: #ffffff;
    border-color: #ffffff;
    transform: translateY(-1px);
  }

  .cta--ghost-ink {
    background-color: transparent;
    color: var(--on-ink);
    border: 1px solid var(--on-ink-border);
  }

  .cta--ghost-ink:hover {
    border-color: var(--on-ink);
    transform: translateY(-1px);
  }

  /* =========================================================================
     CARDS (dossier kit, verbatim). cards--2 is the two-column variant used by
     the exposure removal section; it collapses with the other grids at 880px.
     ========================================================================= */
  .cards {
    list-style: none;
    margin: var(--space-8) 0 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: grid;
    gap: var(--space-5);
  }

  .cards--2 {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
  }

  .cards--3 {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  }

  .cards--4 {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
  }

  .card {
    background-color: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-card);
    padding: var(--space-6);
    transition: box-shadow var(--dur-base) var(--ease-out),
                transform var(--dur-base) var(--ease-out),
                border-color var(--dur-base) var(--ease-out);
  }

  .card:hover {
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-raise);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
    border-color: var(--border-strong);
  }

  /* Static cards: informational only, never navigate. Drop the clickable
     hover-raise so they do not imply interactivity. */
  .card--static:hover {
    box-shadow: none;
    transform: none;
    border-color: var(--border);
  }

  .card__h3 {
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-h3);
    line-height: var(--lh-heading);
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .card__body {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    line-height: var(--lh-snug);
  }

  /* =========================================================================
     TICK LIST (dossier accent marker, mirrors the Home hero point tick).
     A short forest bar, never a dash. Used for architecture + controls.
     ========================================================================= */
  .ticklist {
    list-style: none;
    margin: var(--space-7) 0 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    max-width: 68ch;
  }

  .ticklist__item {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    color: var(--text);
    font-size: var(--text-md);
    line-height: var(--lh-snug);
  }

  .ticklist__item::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 0.62em;
    width: 14px;
    height: 2px;
    background-color: var(--accent);
  }

  /* =========================================================================
     PROOF SPINE (dossier kit, verbatim). proofs--two overrides the three-up
     grid to a two-column layout for the five-item regulatory mapping.
     ========================================================================= */
  .proofs {
    list-style: none;
    margin: var(--space-7) 0 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: var(--space-6);
  }

  .proofs--two {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
  }

  .proof__item {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border-strong);
    padding-top: var(--space-4);
  }

  .proof__label {
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .proof__text {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    line-height: var(--lh-body);
  }

  /* =========================================================================
     DISCLAIMER BLOCK
     ========================================================================= */
  .disclaimer {
    margin: 0;
    border: 1px solid var(--border-strong);
    border-radius: var(--radius-card);
    background-color: var(--bg-card);
    padding: var(--space-6);
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    line-height: var(--lh-body);
    max-width: 78ch;
  }

  /* =========================================================================
     DIAGRAM COLOUR HOOKS (consumed by data-boundary.svg inside Figure).
     Copied verbatim from the Home page. Residency-risk red lives only inside
     the data-boundary diagram, never on page chrome.
     ========================================================================= */
  :global(.fig__svg .diagram) {
    color: #cdd3db;
  }
  :global(.fig__svg .d-faint) {
    stroke: var(--border-strong);
  }
  :global(.fig__svg .d-axis) {
    stroke: var(--border-strong);
  }
  :global(.fig__svg .d-muted) {
    fill: var(--text-muted);
  }
  :global(.fig__svg .d-grey) {
    stroke: var(--grey);
    fill: var(--grey);
  }
  /* hosted-model box on the right path: dark raised surface with grey outline.
     Overrides the SVG's bare white fill (baked for the old light theme). */
  :global(.fig__svg .d-grey-stroke) {
    fill: var(--bg-elevated);
    stroke: var(--grey);
  }
  :global(.fig__svg .d-accent) {
    stroke: var(--accent);
    fill: var(--accent);
  }
  :global(.fig__svg .d-accent-line),
  :global(.fig__svg .d-accent-ring),
  :global(.fig__svg .d-accent-dash) {
    stroke: var(--accent);
  }
  :global(.fig__svg .d-accent-text) {
    fill: var(--accent);
  }
  :global(.fig__svg .d-surface) {
    fill: var(--bg-card);
  }
  :global(.fig__svg .d-risk) {
    stroke: var(--risk);
    fill: var(--risk);
  }
  :global(.fig__svg .d-risk-text) {
    fill: var(--risk);
  }
  :global(.fig__svg .diagram text) {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
  }
  :global(.fig__svg .d-num) {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
  }

  /* =========================================================================
     HERO (single editorial column, no media)
     ========================================================================= */
  .hero {
    position: relative;
    padding-block: var(--space-7) var(--space-8);
  }

  .hero__col {
    max-width: 44rem;
  }

  .hero__meta {
    margin: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-4);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  .hero__tag {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .hero__metasep {
    color: var(--text-faint);
  }

  .hero__h1 {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 0;
    font-size: clamp(40px, 5vw, 64px);
    line-height: var(--lh-tight);
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    max-width: 20ch;
